Relevant information about the dataset:
6819 samples 96 features => all numeric (3 integer and 93 float).

Regarding the 3 integer features, one is our independent variable *bankrupt), the others 2 are categorical data:

- Liability-Assets Flag: 1 if Total Liability exceeds Total Assets, 0 otherwise   
- Net Income Flag: 1 if Net Income is Negative for the last two years, 0 otherwise

There are not columns with null values. Despite the fat that there are not null, there are indicators values equal to zero and also possibility to have outliers in the dataset.

Graphics templates¶

In [14]:
def plot_class_distribution(ind,title):
    
    fig,ax = plt.subplots(1) # axes

    df.iloc[:,ind].value_counts().plot(kind='bar') # data
    plt.title(title, fontdict={'fontsize':16}) # plot title graph
    plt.ylabel("# of companies", fontsize=14) # title axis y 
    plt.xlabel(df.iloc[:,ind].name, fontsize=14) # title axis x
    plt.ylim((0,df.iloc[:,ind].value_counts().max()*1.1)) # y lim axes parameter
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
        
    for p in ax.patches:# plot labels
        ax.annotate('{0:,}'.format(round(p.get_height())), (p.get_x()+p.get_width()/2, p.get_height()),
                xytext=(0, 3),  textcoords="offset points", ha='center', va='bottom')
    
        ax.annotate('{:.01%}'.format(round(p.get_height()/len(df.iloc[:,ind]),2)), (p.get_x()+p.get_width()/2, p.get_height()/2),
                xytext=(60,0), textcoords="offset points", ha='center', va='bottom', color='blue')

Summary Overview¶

Understanding the distribution of Y (bankrupt):

Data below the minimum limit:

As there are a lot of companies with financial indicators equal to zero, we will try to understand the situation from a more quantitative perspective. It can be useful to count the occurrences of zeros for each feature, and sort them in descending order. This allows us to establish the dominance level for zero entries.

In [10]:

The first two features are categorical data (class 0 and 1), they are not outliers.

Apparently, possibly the other indicators can also not be outliers. For example:

  • The indicator "long-term liabilities" represents financial obligations of a company that are due more than one year in the future. Therefore, probably the companies whose indicator is zero do not have long-term liabilities.

  • Also the companies which the indicator "research and development expense rate" is equal to zero, probably, not incurs R&D expenses in the process of finding and creating new products or services.

  • Companies that do not have inventory, will have the indicator "inventory/current Liability" equal to zero.

Similar explanations can be done for the others indicators.

Data above the maximum limit:

When we look for the boxplots generated (see the previous section), we can observe that many of the indicators that have data above the maximum limit are related to rates. These rates can have high values when divided by numbers close to zero.

Considerations:

We could not remove data considering the limits calculated (Q1-1,5 IQR, Q3+1,5 IQR), looking only for each feature individually. The data seems reasonable and consistent. Maybe, we could try to identify if there are some outliers analysing clusters.

To optimize time, whe decided select the features, create and run the models and see how these data will affect the model. Them we define how to deal with it.

Partition the data in training and testing¶

Stratified Train-Test Splits

Our classification problems do not have a balanced number of examples for each class label. As such, it is desirable to split the dataset into train and test sets in a way that preserves the same proportions of examples in each class as observed in the original dataset.

We can achieve this by setting the “stratify” argument to the y component of the original dataset. This will be used by the train_test_split() function to ensure that both the train and test sets have the proportion of examples in each class that is present in the provided “y” array.

In [24]:
X = df.iloc[:,1:]
y = df.iloc[:,0]
In [25]:
# split into train test sets

Selecting the main features¶

Performe feature analyses to determine the most influential features, eliminating redundant or less relevant ones.

Three benefits of performing feature selection before modeling your data are:

  • Reduces Overfitting: Less redundant data means less opportunity to make decisions based on noise.
  • Improves Accuracy: Less misleading data means modeling accuracy improves.
  • Reduces Training Time: Less data means that algorithms train faster.

To select the features we will ranking the features based in tree-based estimators (decision trees) and RFECV.

Although selecting features based on decision trees already consider correlations, we will calculate these parameters separately to help us in the analysis.

Feature selection using SelectFromModel¶¶

SelectFromModel is a meta-transformer that can be used with an estimator to select features based in your importance (featureimportances). Other features are desconsidered and removed if the corresponding importance of them are below the provided threshold parameter (“median”). It is possible also use the max_features parameter to set a limit of the number of features to select.

Tree-based feature selection¶¶

Tree-based estimators can be used to compute impurity-based feature importances, which in turn can be used to discard irrelevant features (when coupled with the SelectFromModel meta-transformer):

In [27]:
def tree_based_feature_selection(X, y):
    
    from pandas.core.common import flatten
       
    seed(1)
    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier()
    clf = clf.fit(X, y)
    df_feat_importance = pd.DataFrame(clf.feature_importances_, index=X.columns, columns=['feat_importance'])
        
    selector = SelectFromModel(clf, threshold='median')
    X_new = selector.fit_transform(X, y)
    # [trans.get_support]: Get a mask, or integer index, of the features selected
    df_feat_retained_decision_tree = pd.DataFrame(X.columns[selector.get_support()].values,columns=['features'])
    
    data = {'features':X.columns.values,
            'importance':clf.feature_importances_,
            'select_tree': selector.get_support()}
            
    df_tree = pd.DataFrame(data)
       
    return df_feat_importance, df_feat_retained_decision_tree, df_tree

df_feat_importance, df_feat_retained_decision_tree, df_tree = tree_based_feature_selection(X_train, y_train)

Recursive feature elimination¶

Given an external estimator that assigns weights to features, the goal of recursive feature elimination (RFE) is to select features by recursively considering smaller and smaller sets of features. First, the estimator is trained on the initial set of features and the importance of each feature is obtained either through any specific attribute (such as coef_, featureimportances) or callable. Then, the least important features are pruned from current set of features. That procedure is recursively repeated on the pruned set until the desired number of features to select is eventually reached (Skit-learn).

RFECV performs RFE in a cross-validation loop to find the optimal number of features.

In [32]:
def tree_rfecv_feature_selection(X, y):
    
    seed(1) 
    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier()
    trans = RFECV(clf)
    X_new = trans.fit_transform(X, y)
   
    df_feat_retained_rfecv = pd.DataFrame(X.columns[trans.get_support()].values, columns = ['features'])
    
    data = {'features':X.columns.values,
             'rank_rfecv':trans.ranking_,
             'selected_rfecv': trans.support_}
    
    df_rfecv = pd.DataFrame(data)
        
    return df_feat_retained_rfecv, df_rfecv
    
df_feat_retained_rfecv, df_rfecv = tree_rfecv_feature_selection(X_train, y_train)
